The introduction of large language models and other similar AI tools has greatly changed teaching and learning at all levels. Most of the literature responding to this has focused on how to detect, discourage, or otherwise deal with the use of these tools by students. This experience report discusses an intervention in a senior capstone course in which students were required to use the tools throughout a semester-long theme assignment. At each stage, students were also required to reflect on their performance and that of the tool. The paper reports on the lessons learned about both the assignments and the overall approach of requiring such usage.